The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Click mouse, pay motor tax 
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Click mouse, pay motor tax 
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar April 7: Long queues in front of the regional transport offices to pay motor vehicle tax or apply for a license or permit of commercial vehicles will soon be pass. Residents in Orissa now have an e-solution at hand.        
	The state transport department today launched e-disha, the countrys first system that will allow payment of fees and motor vehicle tax online.         
	With this, Orissa becomes the first state in the country to simultaneously introduce online services for three facilities  online payment of tax and fee, web-based application and appointment system for learners licence and issuance of vehicle permits, said state transport commissioner CTM Suguna.        
	An efficient and vibrant road transport system in a state is the most essential ingredient for long-term socio-economic and cultural prosperity. It has a direct bearing on the quality of lives, said chief minister Naveen Patnaik while inaugurating e-disha today.         
	The system allows you to verify past payments of the vehicle and evaluate the current tax payable, said Suguna.         
	Many a times dealers of old vehicles fake registration papers and sell off stolen vehicles. Some also fake the year of manufacture of the vehicle to fetch a better price. Our web-based portal gives convenient access to view record about the ownership and year of make of vehicle, she said.        
	The payment application has been integrated with the State Bank of India. The applicants need to have an SBI account with net banking facility to avail services. The online services will gradually be integrated with other banks.        
	Gradually all the processes of the transport department will be computerised and the data made available through Internet or SMS, said Suguna.                                                                                                                                                           
